segments.text: and his head is bald, but he's got fringes of hair.

And then one of my former students, rice farmer from Beaumont, and I don't remember the other one, but I was one of the eight first people that were recognized by this school of agriculture and biology or what, biology.
Do you have any favorite amusing memories, funny moments?
I had a really satisfying experience at A&M, except I didn't get the salary I deserved.
And I think that there's too many people that get recognized not for what they've done, but what they've given A&M.
That's one thing that I'm bothered by.
Last question, what feelings do you have in your heart about A&M?
Well, I really am grateful to A&M, but I also feel like that I have contributed to A&M in a way that very few other people have contributed to A&M since the school was down to 2,000 in enrollments.
And I suspect there are many thousand youngsters all over the world that owe you a great debt of gratitude for the help you gave them in their basic courses.
I believe that's true, and I hope you don't misunderstand me.
